The P229 is one of the most popular SIG SAUER pistols ever made, and carried by thousands of law enforcement professionals throughout the country. The compact size of the P229R makes it ideal for concealed carry. The P226, like the other members of the SIG Classic family, operates by the locked breech short-recoil method pioneered by John Browning. On firing, the slide and barrel are locked together for a few millimeters of rearward movement, after which the barrel is cammed down at the rear. By this time the bullet has left the barrel and the pressure has dropped to safe levels, whereupon the slide completes the rearward stroke, ejecting the spent cartridge. title: For Sale:  2 x ASC-H ADVANCE SQUAD CARBINE SPECIAL FORCE SERIES
postcontent:
Two ASC-H Carbines, NEW IN BOX!!! $200 EACH!!!  Call REDACTED for info.

The ASC-H, or Advanced Squad Carbine – Heavy, is the beefed up bother of the ASC previously released from ECHO 1. It features a larger 7.62mm style magazine and has a slightly bigger lower receiver. While externally this rifle might just look like a more muscular version of the ASC, internally the two rifles are worlds apart. This rifle is cloned after its VFC counterpart and therefore inherited many of its innovative features.

One of the most noteworthy things about this model is that the whole rifle can be broken down after pushing out only one body pin. The rifle uses contact plates at disassembly points instead of fishing the wires through the body which allows it to be field stripped in under thirty seconds. Then by loosening six captured screws you are able to lift the whole barrel group out of the upper receiver. The rifles feature laser etched markings and are finished in a non-reflective flat finish giving them a more tactical appearance than previous models. Overall the ASC-H is a well built rifle with a long list of features.

•Metal upper receiver with polymer lower. 
•Compatible with VFC Mk. 17 series magazines. 
•6 position retractable side folding stock, locks in open position. 
•Flip-up front and rear sights are adjustable and can be removed if desired. 
•4 sling attachment points. 
•MIL-STD-1913 Picatinny rails on top, sides and under barrel. 
•Ambidextrous selector switches and mag catch. 
•Functional bolt catch. 
•14mm CCW threaded muzzle. 
•Metal Version 2 gearbox. 
•Steel gears running on 7mm bearing bushings. 

When we locked in one of its magazines and turned this bruiser loose on the range it quickly proved it has the muscle to back up its looks. Clocking in at an average of 400 fps at the muzzle this rifle quickly disintegrated our target and with only small amount of its massive high capacity magazine depleted it was ready for more. With a 9.6v battery the ASC-H pumps out a steady 700 rounds per minute which is only slightly faster than that of its real steel counterpart. ECHO 1 ships this rifle with a custom 9.6v battery pack although we found you are able to use a regular mini type 9.6v battery in the rifle which only inhibits you from collapsing the stock to its last position.

For those of you who have been wanting to get your hands on one of these rifles but could not quite see dropping the money for a VFC, the ECHO 1 ASC-H has certainty proven that it is a highly capable rifle which offers a lot of bang for your buck.

title: For Sale:  Mauser P-38 K BYF-44 Threaded Barrel For Silencer
postcontent: P-38 byf-44 9mm with all matching numbers, all solid steel, all original phosphate finish and with the barrel threaded for a silencer! No silencer comes with it! You must get a special permit to put one on it! This is a very rarely seen and very unique German WWII P-38! It is a GI's war trophy bringback, it is Not Russian, Not import marked, Not dipped, Not refinished! It is the wonderful original German Mauser Phosphate finish from 1944! Of course there is no way to prove if the gun came straight from the Mauser factory with the threaded barrel! But there is what appears to be original phosphate finish in the threads, that is the only sign it could be so. The gun could also have been made up by the German police, SS or other Gestapo group at a field repair depot, or even a captured arms plant like FN in Belgium for example. Just like they made up so many K98 sniper rifles! The gun could have been made up by the French or Belgian resistance is another possibility. Of course it could have been made up with the silencer stateside by the Mafia! There is just no way to prove or know anything for sure, so you must decide for yourself! The gun does have all original, all phosphate finish, a scarce variation in itself! Most are dual-tone. It does have the normally seen blued parts, trigger, rear sight, and magazine. The bore is mirror bright with deep rifling, there is a mark or partial ring in the bore, near the muzzle, apparently from being threaded so deep. The pistol functions just fine but you must have your gunsmith inspect and approve it before firing. This is a fantastic find! Could be Gestapo, resistance or Mafia! A World War II P-38 with threaded barrel for a silencer!

TAVOR SAR Flattop 16.5" Barrel Black Finish

At the end of the 1982 Israel-Lebanon War arose an understanding that the modern battlefield had changed. One of the conclusions from the war, particularly relevant to the small arms industry, was that the battle had moved from open field conflicts to close-quarters engagements – and there was a need for a seamless transition from daylight to nighttime capability on a single mission. Out of this understanding, and after more than a decade of collaboration and testing with the Israel Defense Forces (IDF) - the TAVOR® rifle was born. Just as race car technology trickles down to consumer automobiles, so do these time and battle-tested firearms now become a modern sporting rifle platform for civilian gun enthusiasts.

The TAVOR® is a perfect fusion of an ordnance grade steel receiver coupled to a Mil-Spec cold hammer forged barrel and encased into a high-impact strength polymer uni-body with exceptional situational ergonomics. The ultra-compact form factor allows for easy transitions in close quarter situations…or even in your favorite deer blind. The bullpup design moves the center of gravity of the rifle closer to the users’ body allowing for more instinctive aiming and improved acquisition time to target. This innovative design also allows for a full length barrel, which means no loss of down range ballistic accuracy. Near and far range accuracy is enhanced by the minimized recoil provided by a non-lubricated long stroke gas piston system. With the exception of a hand-specific locking bolt, the rifle is completely ambidextrous allowing for easy left-hand conversion of the operating handle, ejection port, fire-control safety, sling swivel receptacles and fore-mounted accessory Picatinny rail. The TAVOR® is supplied with IDF-tested and approved magazines – but you can also use your own AR-15/M16 style magazines.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Us Military M3 Infrared Sniper Scope 20,000 volts
location: NW Suburbs, Minneapolis / St. Paul, Minnesota
postcontent:
For sale and maybe partial trade is my Korea Era  Us military Sniper Scope. Known officially as: M3, sniperscope, infrared, set no. 1, 20,000 volts. Made by american optical co. Buffalo, NY 6-23-51. Made to be mounted on a special M1 carbine known as the M2 carbine making the whole setup a M3. 

Very good condition. Really nice for how old it is. How does it compare to others? I don't know. I've never seen one that wasn't in a book or on the internet. This is the only one I have ever seen. Very rare, very cool piece of American Military History.

What is there and what isn't. This comes with the IR scope, IR Light, Foregrip/ Handle with the trigger, power transformer box, all necessary original wiring, 1 tube, original rubberized backpack(nice), and original chest. As far as what is missing? I'm really no expert but I think there was a tool set and more tubes. These are not there. And of course no .30 carbine. No rust anywhere and looks to be the original finish. Some scratches on the scope but not bad. A little corrosion on a small copper piece behind the light source. And it looks like the red filter is a little rough. The outside plastic of the light source is fine, its the red filter inside. I have not taken this apart or tried to clean any of it. 

Because this is so rare I did not want auction it, I wanted a lot of people to have a shot at owning it. Same with gun broker. I found it in Mn I would like a collector in MN to give it a good home. So I figured the only fair way to do it wold be to take offers. So, if you want it, take a shot at it and email me your best offer. If you know what it is, you know what its worth, and how often you can find one.

As far as trades go... I might, might, take one of the following as partial trade with cash. 1. Ruger .44 carbine semi-auto. Prefer older tube fed. 2. Ruger No. 1 in 270 win, 280 rem, 30.06 or 303 brit. 3. HK usp Tactical all black. Of course these guns must be nice.

Of course all cash is always nice. FTF meet. Leave your name and number or I will not get back to you.

Thanks for looking.
